## What happened

**.NET 11 dropped the macOS DSA implementation.** On macOS, .NET's `DSA` class was backed by Apple's Security/CommonCrypto framework, but Apple has deprecated and removed DSA support from its crypto APIs. Microsoft followed suit — `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS in .NET 11. (Windows and Linux still work because they use CNG and OpenSSL respectively, both of which still support DSA.)

## How to fix it

You have a few options, depending on your constraints:

### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended for legacy verification)
If you only need to **verify** existing DSA signatures, pull in [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography):

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

// Import your existing DSA public key
var publicKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);
var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);
verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

This is a pure managed implementation — no OS crypto dependency, works on all platforms.

### Option 2 — Bind OpenSSL on macOS
Install OpenSSL via Homebrew (`brew install openssl`) and P/Invoke into `libssl`/`libcrypto`. This is fragile and adds a deployment dependency — generally not recommended unless you already depend on a native OpenSSL binding.

### Option 3 — Migrate off DSA entirely (best long-term)
DSA is a legacy algorithm (NIST deprecated it in FIPS 186-5). Re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, both of which are supported cross-platform in .NET:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);
byte[] sig = ecdsa.SignData(data, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

## Recommended path

Use **BouncyCastle now** to keep legacy verification working cross-platform, and **plan a migration to ECDSA/Ed25519** for new signatures so you can eventually drop DSA entirely.
